  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!-- Document body                                                 -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <component>
    <structuredBody>

      <!-- Chief Complaint -->
      <component>
        <section>
          <code code="46239-0" codeSystem="2.16.840.1.113883.6.1"
                codeSystemName="LOINC" displayName="Chief Complaint"/>
          <title>Chief Complaint</title>
          <text>
            <paragraph>Patient presents stating, "I think I might need glasses, but
            also maybe everyone else is just fuzzy." He arrived 20 minutes late
            because he "couldn't find the entrance," which he now acknowledges was
            the exit. He also attempted to check in at the periodontist next door,
            a mistake he made at last year's appointment as well. He greeted the
            receptionist as "Doctor," and attempted to sit in her chair.</paragraph>
          </text>
        </section>
      </component>

      <!-- History of Present Illness -->
      <component>
        <section>
          <code code="10164-2" codeSystem="2.16.840.1.113883.6.1"
                codeSystemName="LOINC" displayName="History of Present Illness"/>
          <title>History of Present Illness</title>
          <text>
            <paragraph>Mr. Kubota, age 46, reports that he has been wearing a pair
            of spectacles he found at a park in 2021 after a drop. He assumed they
            were his because "they were the right color." For five years he has been
            reading street signs by asking nearby strangers, attributing the habit to
            "enjoying community interaction." He attributed his increasingly blurred
            vision to "the general mystery of existence" and "the soft-focus
            aesthetic of modern life."</paragraph>

            <paragraph>He reports no prior eye examinations, as he was "pretty
            confident his eyes were fine based on the fact that he can see the sun."
            When asked whether the sun appeared blurry, he paused for an unusually
            long time before answering "define blurry."</paragraph>

            <paragraph>Denies diplopia, though he admits he believed he had twins
            for approximately six months in 2024. The twins were his refrigerator
            and the recycling bin, which are, by all accounts, not twins, not
            related, and not the same size.</paragraph>

            <paragraph>Patient reports that he navigated to this clinic using a
            method he describes as "confident walking." He passed the correct
            building twice before a stranger pointed at the sign. He could not read
            the sign but appreciated the gesture.</paragraph>
          </text>
        </section>
      </component>

      <!-- Examination -->
      <component>
        <section>
          <code code="29545-1" codeSystem="2.16.840.1.113883.6.1"
                codeSystemName="LOINC" displayName="Physical Findings"/>
          <title>Examination</title>
          <text>
            <paragraph>Visual Acuity (with found glasses,
            Rx unknown, likely -1.00 OD/OS):</paragraph>
            <list listType="unordered">
              <item>OD (Right): 20/400. Patient read the large "E" as "F", then
              reconsidered: "maybe a table?" Became briefly philosophical about
              the nature of letters.</item>
              <item>OS (Left): 20/200. Patient was more confident, reading the "E"
              as "definitely a letter. Could be several."</item>
            </list>

            <paragraph>Visual Acuity (with correct prescription, -3.50 OD /
            -3.25 OS):</paragraph>
            <list listType="unordered">
              <item>OD: 20/20</item>
              <item>OS: 20/20</item>
            </list>

            <paragraph>Patient stared at the corrected Snellen chart for 45
            seconds in what can only be described as "philosophical shock." He
            then asked if the letters had always been there. He was informed that
            yes, they had. He asked about the chart on the wall behind him as well.
            He was told that was a motivational poster. He read it aloud. It said
            "Hang in There." He found this personally meaningful.</paragraph>

            <paragraph>Extraocular Movements: Full range of motion, intact. Patient
            tracked the penlight with his entire head, ostrich-style, rather than
            eye movement alone. Counseled on technique.</paragraph>

            <paragraph>Pupils: Equal, round, and reactive to light. Patient reported
            that light was "louder than expected" and asked if that was
            normal.</paragraph>

            <paragraph>Slit Lamp: Unremarkable. No corneal foreign bodies. Mild
            anterior surface dryness noted, consistent with prolonged screen use
            without blinking, which patient confirmed is his "primary hobby and
            also secondary hobby."</paragraph>

            <paragraph>Fundus Exam: Normal optic disc, healthy cup-to-disc ratio.
            Normal macula. No signs of mistake-related ocular trauma. No diabetic
            or hypertensive changes. No evidence of prior retinal detachment,
            which is a statistical near-miracle given the prescription.</paragraph>
          </text>
        </section>
      </component>

      <!-- Assessment and Plan -->
      <component>
        <section>
          <code code="51847-2" codeSystem="2.16.840.1.113883.6.1"
                codeSystemName="LOINC" displayName="Assessment and Plan"/>
          <title>Assessment and Plan</title>
          <text>
            <paragraph>ASSESSMENT:</paragraph>
            <list listType="ordered">
              <item>MYOPIA, BILATERAL, MODERATE (-3.50 OD / -3.25 OS). Correctable
              to 20/20 OU. Remarkable primarily in that it went unaddressed for five
              years, during which the patient successfully navigated urban environments
              using social engineering and ambient crowd behavior.</item>

              <item>INAPPROPRIATE SPECTACLE CORRECTION, CHRONIC x5 YEARS
              (crowd-sourced, wrong prescription). Patient to discontinue use
              immediately. Clinician regrets not being present for the moment
              patient first put on the correct glasses and saw a bird clearly
              for what may have been the first time as an adult.</item>

              <item>OCULAR SURFACE DRYNESS, MILD, SCREEN-INDUCED. No staining.
              Consistent with "never blinking," which patient has confirmed is
              his preferred screen-viewing technique.</item>

              <item>ACUTE EXISTENTIAL VISUAL ADJUSTMENT. Patient was visibly moved
              upon discovering that trees have individual leaves. He had previously
              assumed they were "green clouds." He asked if clouds were also
              different. He was told yes. He sat with this for a moment.</item>
            </list>

            <paragraph>PLAN:</paragraph>
            <list listType="ordered">
              <item>New spectacle prescription issued: OD -3.50 sphere, OS -3.25
              sphere. Patient strongly counseled to obtain spectacles from a licensed
              optician rather than the lost-and-found bin of a food service
              establishment.</item>
              <item>Preservative-free artificial tears, 1-2 drops OU TID PRN
              dryness. Patient also counseled that blinking is free and
              encouraged.</item>
              <item>Patient instructed to look at a tree before next appointment
              and confirm it has leaves. This is a medical instruction.</item>
              <item>Return to clinic in 12 months, or sooner if patient once again
              mistakes an exit for an entrance, acquires eyewear from a restaurant
              floor, or identifies a major appliance as a family member.</item>
            </list>

            <paragraph>FINAL VISUAL ACUITY: 20/20 OU with appropriate correction.
            PROGNOSIS: Excellent, contingent upon patient compliance with the concept
            of "wearing one's own glasses."</paragraph>

            <paragraph>-- Dr. Seymour Clearly, O.D.
            20/20 Vision Center and Novelty Eyewear Emporium
            "We See You. You Should See Us."</paragraph>
          </text>
        </section>
      </component>

    </structuredBody>
  </component>

</ClinicalDocument>
